solution:
We have that:
:$\displaystyle \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i = 1 + 2 + \cdots + n$
Consider $\displaystyle 2 \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i$.
Then:

2 \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i = 2 \paren {1 + 2 + \dotsb + \paren {n - 1} + n}
\paren {1 + 2 + \dotsb + \paren {n - 1} + n} + \paren {n + \paren {n - 1} + \dotsb + 2 + 1}
\paren {1 + n} + \paren {2 + \paren {n - 1} } + \dotsb + \paren {\paren {n - 1} + 2} + \paren {n + 1} (Integer Addition is Commutative, Integer Addition is Associative)
\paren {n + 1}_1 + \paren {n + 1}_2 + \dotsb + \paren {n + 1}_n
n \paren {n + 1}

So:

2 \sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i = n \paren {n + 1}
\sum_{i \mathop = 1}^n i = \frac {n \paren {n + 1} } 2

